Apple and Antitrust for Aggregators
-----------------------------------

I know that there has been a lot of Apple antitrust talk this week, but (1)=
 it=E2=80=99s obviously a huge story, (2) there aren=E2=80=99t any other ma=
jor happenings this week, and (3) there is one more point that I think is v=
ery important to make: there was a very cogent antitrust case to make again=
st Apple, with an emphasis on the past tense; unfortunately, the Supreme Co=
urt took it off the table in 2019.

At a high level, Apple, particularly when it comes to apps, is an Aggregato=
r: this means they control demand (iPhone users), and have power over suppl=
iers (iPhone developers). That is why they can charge a 30% tax without the=
re being any meaningful impact on end-user pricing, first because most deve=
lopers are commoditized, and second because even differentiated developers =
have no choice but to pay Apple in order to keep their customers happy. It =
follows, then, that the group that needs antitrust protection from Apple is=
 not consumers but rather developers.

This is a critical question for antitrust, because only one of the two grou=
ps can have standing to sue about App Store fees. I explained why in 2018=
=E2=80=99s Antitrust, the App Store, and Apple ( https://stratechery.com/20=
18/antitrust-the-app-store-and-apple/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsIm=
tpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJz=
