IhT1zpu032_17-u_1HcKjof9QqtHchSo5QbWurA ) , which covered a lawsuit from Ap=
ple consumers ( Pepper ) alleging that they were overcharged for iOS apps b=
ecause of Apple=E2=80=99s monopolistic control of the App Store:

The question before the Supreme Court is whether or not Pepper et al. have =
standing to sue Apple for antitrust violations at all; in other words, the =
case =E2=80=94 which was launched in 2011 =E2=80=94 hasn=E2=80=99t even sta=
rted yet. The Clayton Antitrust Act of 1914 stated that =E2=80=9Cany person=
 who shall be injured in his business or property by reasons of anything fo=
rbidden in the antitrust laws=E2=80=9D can bring an antitrust action, but i=
n the 1977 case Illinois Brick Co. v. Illinois , the Supreme Court held tha=
t only direct purchasers of illegally priced goods had standing to sue.

The specifics of the Illinois Brick case are helpful in parsing out what ma=
kes the Apple case complex; specifically, the Illinois Brick value chain wa=
s very straightforward: concrete block makers (including the eponymous Illi=
nois Brick Company) were accused of colluding to fix prices for concrete bl=
ocks, which were bought by masonry contractors; masonry contractors in turn=
 submitted bids to general contractors for construction projects, which wer=
e ultimately paid for by the State of Illinois. The State of Illinois sued =
for damages, alleging that the higher prices resulting from the price fixin=
g had been passed through to the State of Illinois.

