Frankly, I do believe that developers are being harmed by Apple=E2=80=99s p=
olicies, and I do believe those policies are illegal. The implication of th=
at, though, is that it is developers who should have the right to sue Apple=
, not consumers. Indeed, the majority=E2=80=99s arguments ( https://casetex=
t.com/case/apple-inc-v-pepper-2 ) that there would not be a sort of =E2=80=
=9Cdouble jeopardy=E2=80=9D with regards to damages =E2=80=94 one of the mo=
tivating factors behind the Illinois Brick decision in the first place =E2=
=80=94 is not at all compelling:

Apple claims that allowing consumers to sue will result in =E2=80=9Cconflic=
ting claims to a common fund=E2=80=94the amount of the alleged overcharge.=
=E2=80=9D Apple is incorrect. This is not a case where multiple parties at =
different levels of a distribution chain are trying to all recover the same=
 passed-through overcharge initially levied by the manufacturer at the top =
of the chain.

I honestly don=E2=80=99t understand this argument: there is one alleged ove=
rcharge =E2=80=94 Apple=E2=80=99s 30% commission =E2=80=94 and it is hard t=
o understand how it is that both consumers and developers can have a case w=
ithout both seeking =E2=80=9Cthe same passed-through overcharge=E2=80=9D. T=
he dissent makes the same point:

Courts will have to divvy up the commissions Apple collected between the de=
velopers and the consumers. To do that, they=E2=80=99ll have to figure out =
which party bore what portion of the overcharge in every purchase. And if t=
he developers bring suit separately from the consumers, Apple might be at r=
isk of duplicative damages awards totaling more than the full amount it col=
lected in commissions.

As both the majority and dissent note, the entire reason behind the Illinoi=
s Brick decision was to avoid exactly these sorts of determinations: having=
 one set of damages pursued by two distinct parties is both impractical and=
 overreaching when it comes to judicial power. That the majority waves away=
 this point is shocking.

There is, I would note, one other angle for a developer lawsuit that didn=
=E2=80=99t exist at that time: App Tracking Transparency. I wrote yesterday=
 ( https://stratechery.com/2024/apple-and-the-monopoly-question-iphone-mark=
