DMA Investigations and Apple=E2=80=99s Risk
-----------------------------------

I=E2=80=99m going to knock this one out quick, just so we can get all of th=
is regulatory stuff out of the way before the week is over. From a European=
 Commission press release ( https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/det=
ail/en/ip_24_1689 ) :

Today, the Commission has opened non-compliance investigations under the Di=
gital Markets Act (DMA) into Alphabet=E2=80=99s rules on steering in Google=
 Play and self-preferencing on Google Search, Apple=E2=80=99s rules on stee=
ring in the App Store and the choice screen for Safari and Meta=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Cpay or consent model=E2=80=9D. The Commission suspects that the me=
asures put in place by these gatekeepers fall short of effective compliance=
 of their obligations under the DMA.

In addition, the Commission has launched investigatory steps relating to Ap=
ple=E2=80=99s new fee structure for alternative app stores and Amazon=E2=80=
=99s ranking practices on its marketplace. Finally, the Commission has orde=
red gatekeepers to retain certain documents to monitor the effective implem=
entation and compliance with their obligations.

Well, that didn=E2=80=99t take long, and speaks to one of the biggest flaws=
 with European regulation: it=E2=80=99s completely vague and you only know =
if you=E2=80=99re in compliance if you do not get investigated. Oops!

Of the actions listed, the Meta one is both the most unjust, and the most s=
urprising: there is nothing in the DMA explicitly about data collection; ra=
ther, the justification appears to be that it is =E2=80=9Cunfair.=E2=80=9D =
Never mind that demanding a company provide its services at a business mode=
l of regulators=E2=80=99 own choosing =E2=80=94 which apparently is only un=
targeted ads =E2=80=94=C2=A0is very much unfair. Meta is offering users the=
 choice of targeted ads or paying a subscription fee; the latter is an emin=
ently reasonable alternative for European citizens who don=E2=80=99t want t=
heir data collected. To insist that Meta=E2=80=99s products must remain fre=
e with drastically less profitable un-targeted ads is bordering on national=
ization (continentalization?).

Indeed, a ruling against Meta in this instance would absolutely justify Met=
a=E2=80=99s withdrawal from the E.U. completely: why should the company pro=
vide a service when it is barred from monetizing it, with or without user d=
ata? In truth, though, Meta probably doesn=E2=80=99t have any choice but to=
 go along: the value of a network is a function of how many people are on t=
hat network, and while most people=E2=80=99s networks are surely intra-cont=
inental, there are inter-continental connections as well; in other words, c=
utting off E.U. countries from Meta apps would make the product worse for M=
eta=E2=80=99s customers outside of the E.U.

It=E2=80=99s worth pointing out that the situation is meaningfully differen=
t for Apple in particular. John Gruber has a post at Daring Fireball ( http=
s://daringfireball.net/2024/03/eu_share_of_apples_revenue ) highlighting th=
e relatively small amount of money Apple makes in the E.U.:

A few readers have asked about my speculation ( https://daringfireball.net/=
2024/03/ec_non_compliance_investigations ) that Apple, along with the other=
 DMA-designated gatekeepers (none of which are European companies of course=
), might reasonably pull out of the relatively small EU market rather than =
risk facing disproportionately large fines from the European Commission. Th=
e DMA allows the EC to fine gatekeepers up to 10 percent of global revenue =
(which would hit a hardware-based company like Apple particularly hard) for=
 a first offense, and up to 20 percent for subsequent fines. But the EU rep=
resents only 7 percent of Apple=E2=80=99s revenue. That figure comes from C=
FO Luca Maestri on Apple=E2=80=99s Q1 2024 analyst call ( https://sixcolors=
.com/post/2024/02/this-is-tim-transcript-of-apples-q1-2024-analyst-call/ ).

Gruber=E2=80=99s point about hardware is important in two respects:

* First, as Gruber notes, Apple=E2=80=99s revenues are much higher than adv=
ertising-based companies, particularly on a per-user basis, but that is in =
part because their costs are much higher =E2=80=94 they have to actually ma=
ke the phones! The E.U. fine structure, though, doesn=E2=80=99t make any pr=
ovision for cost structures, which means Apple is uniquely at risk from fin=
es based on worldwide revenue (the situation is even worse for Amazon).
* Second, the implication of Apple being a hardware company is that they ar=
e not primarily a network-effects based service (because no hardware compan=
y can serve the whole market, and iMessage is not widely used in the E.U.).=
 Yes, Apple=E2=80=99s business model has networks effects =E2=80=94 the App=
 Store is a two-sided network of developers and users =E2=80=94 but it=E2=
=80=99s not a Meta-style peer-to-peer network whose value is a function of =
the number of participants; Apple just needs a sufficient number of develop=
ers and users to attract the other, and they would have that absent the E.U=
.

All of that is to say that I think that Gruber=E2=80=99s warning that Apple=
 might consider leaving the E.U. should be taken seriously. Indeed, I would=
 go further: you can make the case that Apple is being foolhardy in not lea=
ving the E.U., given the size of the potential fines relative to the E.U.=
=E2=80=99s contribution to Apple=E2=80=99s bottom line, and relative unimpo=
rtance to Apple=E2=80=99s overall business.

That said, I don=E2=80=99t expect that to happen soon, if at all: whatever =
you think of Apple=E2=80=99s E.U. compliance plans ( https://stratechery.co=
